defs.docs: # hibitset

defs.name: AtomicBitSet
defs.docs:
This is similar to a [`BitSet`] but allows setting of value
 without unique ownership of the structure

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates an empty `AtomicBitSet`.

defs.name: add_atomic
defs.docs:
Adds `id` to the `AtomicBitSet`. Returns `true` if the value was
 already in the set.

defs.name: add
defs.docs:
Adds `id` to the `BitSet`. Returns `true` if the value was
 already in the set.

defs.name: remove
defs.docs:
Removes `id` from the set, returns `true` if the value
 was removed, and `false` if the value was not set
 to begin with.

defs.name: contains
defs.docs: Returns `true` if `id` is in the set.

defs.name: clear
defs.docs: Clear all bits in the set

defs.name: DrainBitIter
defs.docs: A draining `Iterator` over a [`DrainableBitSet`] structure.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn (set: &'a mut T, masks: [usize; LAYERS], prefix: [u32; LAYERS - 1]) -> Self
defs.docs:
Creates a new `DrainBitIter`. You usually don't call this function
 but just [`.drain()`] on a bit set.

defs.name: BitParIter
defs.docs: A `ParallelIterator` over a [`BitSetLike`] structure.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a new `BitParIter`. You usually don't call this function
 but just [`.par_iter()`] on a bit set.

defs.name: layers_split
defs.docs: Sets how many layers are split when forking.

defs.name: BitProducer
defs.docs: Allows splitting and internally iterating through `BitSet`.

defs.name: BitIter
defs.docs: An `Iterator` over a [`BitSetLike`] structure.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn (set: T, masks: [usize; LAYERS], prefix: [u32; LAYERS - 1]) -> Self
defs.docs:
Creates a new `BitIter`. You usually don't call this function
 but just [`.iter()`] on a bit set.

defs.name: contains
defs.docs: Allows checking if set bit is contained in underlying bit set.

defs.name: BitSetAnd
defs.docs:
`BitSetAnd` takes two [`BitSetLike`] items, and merges the masks
 returning a new virtual set, which represents an intersection of the
 two original sets.

defs.name: BitSetOr
defs.docs:
`BitSetOr` takes two [`BitSetLike`] items, and merges the masks
 returning a new virtual set, which represents an merged of the
 two original sets.

defs.name: BitSetNot
defs.docs:
`BitSetNot` takes a [`BitSetLike`] item, and produced an inverted virtual set.
 Note: the implementation is sub-optimal because layers 1-3 are not active.

defs.name: BitSetXor
defs.docs:
`BitSetXor` takes two [`BitSetLike`] items, and merges the masks
 returning a new virtual set, which represents an merged of the
 two original sets.

defs.name: BitSetAll
defs.docs:
`BitSetAll` is a bitset with all bits set. Essentially the same as
 `BitSetNot(BitSet::new())` but without any allocation.

defs.name: BitSet
defs.docs:
A `BitSet` is a simple set designed to track which indices are placed
 into it.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates an empty `BitSet`.

defs.name: with_capacity
defs.docs: Creates an empty `BitSet`, preallocated for up to `max` indices.

defs.name: add
defs.docs:
Adds `id` to the `BitSet`. Returns `true` if the value was
 already in the set.

defs.name: remove
defs.docs:
Removes `id` from the set, returns `true` if the value
 was removed, and `false` if the value was not set
 to begin with.

defs.name: contains
defs.docs: Returns `true` if `id` is in the set.

defs.name: clear
defs.docs: Completely wipes out the bit set.

defs.name: BitSetLike
defs.docs: A generic interface for [`BitSetLike`]-like types.

defs.name: get_from_layer
defs.value: fn (&self, layer: usize, idx: usize) -> usize
defs.docs: Gets the `usize` corresponding to layer and index.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Returns true if this `BitSetLike` contains nothing, and false otherwise.

defs.name: layer3
defs.docs:
Return a `usize` where each bit represents if any word in layer2
 has been set.

defs.name: layer2
defs.docs:
Return the `usize` from the array of usizes that indicates if any
 bit has been set in layer1

defs.name: layer1
defs.docs:
Return the `usize` from the array of usizes that indicates if any
 bit has been set in layer0

defs.name: layer0
defs.docs:
Return a `usize` that maps to the direct 1:1 association with
 each index of the set

defs.name: contains
defs.docs: Allows checking if set bit is contained in the bit set.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs: Create an iterator that will scan over the keyspace

defs.name: par_iter
defs.docs: Create a parallel iterator that will scan over the keyspace

defs.name: DrainableBitSet
defs.docs: A extension to the [`BitSetLike`] trait which allows draining it.

defs.name: remove
defs.docs: Removes bit from the bit set.

defs.name: drain
defs.docs: Create a draining iterator that will scan over the keyspace and clears it while doing so.
